  "text": "We now consider the general case where z is not necessarily small. For given non-resonant V > 0 (such that (12) does not hold), the solution h(ξ) and z of (24) was found numerically as follows. The integrals in the expressions (10) for the Atkinson-Cabrera solution and (23) for the kernel were evaluated numerically in Mathematica using Levin's method for oscillatory integrals [CITATION_1] . The trapezoidal approximation of the integral equation (24) for a finite z (with 100 uniformly distributed mesh points) then yielded a homogeneous linear system Q(z)h = 0. Here h is the vector of values of h(s) at the mesh points. After solving detQ(z) = 0 for z, we obtained the corresponding solution h of Q(z)h = 0, normalized to satisfy (19) in the sense of the trapezoidal approximation. In general, there were more than one root of detQ(z) = 0, but at most one of these yielded admissible solutions that satisfied the generalized admissibility conditions (17) within numerical error. Once the admissible z and h were found, the trapezoidal approximation of the integrals in (27) and (28) was used to compute the solution u(ξ) and the applied stress σ. Fig. 4 shows the solution u(ξ) obtained at V = 0.2 and µ = 1 (black curve) along with the inadmissible Atkinson-Cabrera solution U(ξ) (z = 0, gray curve). In this case z = 0.212. One can see that the obtained solution satisfies the constraints (17) within numerical error (which is of the order of 10 −6 in this case). Repeating this procedure for a range of velocities, we obtain the kinetic relation σ(V ) and the corresponding relation z(V ) between z and V shown in Fig. 5 . Note that z(V ) decreases as V grows and becomes zero at V = V 0 ≈ 0.357. This is the threshold velocity such that q(0) = 0, which equals the bifurcation velocity as predicted in Sec. 4. At Fig. 4 , is shown in Fig. 7a . Note that it approximates the delta-function behavior at ξ = ±z that was predicted in Sec. 4. As V decreases, the shape functions develop oscillations due to the increasingly oscillatory behavior of q(ξ) at smaller V ; see, for example, Fig. 7b for h(ξ) at V = 0.1023.",
